## 4. KEY FINDINGS FROM EXECUTION
================================================================================

FINDING 1: HITL WORKFLOW EVOLVED DURING EXECUTION
The systematic documentation workflow (completion reports per task) was not
established from the start. It emerged iteratively from Task 6 onward.
This demonstrates that prompt engineering methodology improves through practice.

FINDING 2: AUTHORIZATION COMPLEXITY
The most complex migration challenge was replicating AWS Verified Permissions
(Cedar policy language) in application-level RBAC. Task 10 required custom
implementation of entity transformation logic and policy evaluation engine.
This confirms the finding documented in phase2.report regarding AVP as a
first-class concern.

FINDING 3: PET AND ORDER AS GREENFIELD WORK
Consistent with phase2.report recommendation, Pet and Order entities were
implemented as new features rather than migrated from existing FaaS code.
No source data existed for these entities in the FaaS application.

FINDING 4: HEXAGONAL ARCHITECTURE ENABLES MIGRATION
The adoption of Hexagonal Architecture (Ports and Adapters) from Task 4
onward allowed DynamoDB adapters to be developed independently of business
logic, validating the theoretical framework described in thesis section 2.2.

================================================================================
## 5. REPRODUCTION STEPS
================================================================================

To reproduce the Phase 3 migration:
1. Ensure Phase 1 output (docs/output/openapi.yaml) is available
2. Ensure Phase 2 output (docs/output/data-base-definition.txt) is available
3. Execute prompts in prompts/phase3-migration/detailed-migration-plan.txt
   sequentially, using each task output as input for the next
4. Apply Documentation Standards from Task 6 onward:
   create TASK_{N}_COMPLETION_REPORT.md after each task
5. Commit after each task following conventional commits format

